#Git is the distributed version control system. In DCS, each user is managing the version at local level and pushing the final version into the centralized repository such as Github, Gitlab etc.

#Basic git command include:
git init #initializing git
git add <file_name>		#Adding file to git tracking
git commit -m "commit message" <file_name> 	#Adding file in commit area

#Command to set config:
git config --global --edit 	#This will open config file and there we can edit username and email id
git commit --amend --reset-author 	#This command will open an editor where we have to provide new commit and save. This will update author

#Command to pull changes from remote repo
git pull origin master #Note: Here origin is the remote repo which is stored in your local. Origin can be checked via command "git remote -v" and master is the branch name of local. 

"git restore fileName" is the command which unstage the staged file. While unstaging, it also delete the modification done on the file.
Also command "git restore --staged fileName" is used to move file from staging area to track area. In restore from staged area, the current will not be impacted as git restore command in tracked area.

git diff command gives the difference between the file in untracked area.

GIT MERGE
Git merge is a scenario where developer fails to pull code from remote repository before making changes into there local repository. In this scenaria, when the developer will try to push changes to remote repo he/she will face a merge conflict issue. This is known as GIT Merge.

Generally Git merge is resolved by sitting with the developer and understanding who's commit we want to retain and delete the other commit by vi into the file and providing commit.
